## 7. Design Intent Reading

From the photos and renders, Bosco Verticale can be interpreted as a project that redefines high-rise residential living through vegetation.

The design intent can be understood in five main ways:

### 7.1 Bringing nature into high-rise housing

The project allows residents to experience trees and plants directly from their apartments. Nature becomes part of everyday domestic life, not only a distant view.

### 7.2 Creating an environmental buffer

The balcony vegetation acts as a buffer between private interiors and the dense city. It filters sunlight, views, heat, and visual exposure.

### 7.3 Transforming the facade into a living system

The facade is not only a visual surface. It becomes a system that grows, changes, and requires maintenance.

### 7.4 Extending urban greenery vertically

Instead of relying only on ground-level parks, the project extends greenery upward. The tower itself becomes part of the urban green infrastructure.

### 7.5 Producing a new image of residential density

Bosco Verticale suggests that high-density residential towers do not need to be purely glass, concrete, or repetitive. They can also become ecological, seasonal, and visually soft.

---

## 8. Contextual Relationship

Bosco Verticale is strongly connected to its urban surroundings.

The exterior image shows that the towers are located near open green spaces and modern high-rise developments. This context is important because the project acts as a bridge between city and landscape.

The building relates to its context in three ways:

### 8.1 Relationship with public green space

The greenery on the tower visually continues the surrounding park landscape. The building appears as a vertical extension of the ground-level green space.

### 8.2 Relationship with urban skyline

The towers stand out from nearby glass office buildings because their identity comes from vegetation. This makes them recognizable as ecological landmarks.

### 8.3 Relationship with residential life

The green facade improves the relationship between residents and the city. It gives residents privacy, shade, and a closer connection to nature while still living in a dense urban district.

